1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,005
In the next concepts,

2

00:00:02,005  -->  00:00:07,545
we are going to combine what we know about how to calculate the mean with notation.

3

00:00:07,545  -->  00:00:11,700
The purpose of this video is not to relearn how to calculate the mean

4

00:00:11,700  -->  00:00:17,115
but rather to introduce notation using a measure you already know.

5

00:00:17,115  -->  00:00:21,710
Let's consider the amount of time someone spends on our website in minutes.

6

00:00:21,710  -->  00:00:26,220
Imagine we collect the amount of time spent on our site for five individuals.

7

00:00:26,220  -->  00:00:27,900
From the last video,

8

00:00:27,900  -->  00:00:30,905
we saw that we could label the values in this way,

9

00:00:30,905  -->  00:00:33,140
x1 for the first value,

10

00:00:33,140  -->  00:00:35,210
x2 for the second value,

11

00:00:35,210  -->  00:00:38,660
x3 for the third value and so on.

12

00:00:38,660  -->  00:00:42,030
Imagine we want to add the first two numbers together.

13

00:00:42,030  -->  00:00:47,970
We could write this in notation as x1 plus x2 which in this example,

14

00:00:47,970  -->  00:00:51,160
would be the same as 15 plus 10.

15

00:00:51,160  -->  00:00:54,230
If we wanted to add more than just two values,

16

00:00:54,230  -->  00:00:57,920
it would be tedious to continue the same process.

17

00:00:57,920  -->  00:01:00,469
Imagine if we had 100 values.

18

00:01:00,469  -->  00:01:05,239
We would have a, x1 plus x2 plus x3

19

00:01:05,239  -->  00:01:10,545
plus and we'd have to continue this process until x 100.

20

00:01:10,545  -->  00:01:14,150
Someone must have come up with a better way to notate this.

21

00:01:14,150  -->  00:01:17,690
And it turns out, there is a better way.
